Part 2 : EC2, IAM, Security Groups, EBS, AMI, Load Balancer, Target Groups & Health Checks

1. Why did you choose ec2 instead of lambda function
A: I choose ec2 because i needed a persistent linux server where i can install docker, do monitoring,nginx, cloudwatch agent. AWS lambda is serverless and best for 
   short running event driven functions whereas my application needs continuous execution

2. What is EC2?
A: Its a server provided by amazon. Its elastic cloud compute. It allows us to launch instances which can be configured with OS, CPU, memory,storage and networking

3. Explain your ec2 setup
A: I launched ubuntu ec2 with vpc. i connected using ssh using keypair. I installed docker, nginx, cloned the config files from github, built the docker image, ran 
   the flask application inside the docker container. I then configured nginx as reverse proxy and registered the instance with a load balancer

4. Explain your project request flow
A: User --> Application load balancer (divides traffic btwn healthy instances) --> EC2 --> Nginx (acts as reverseproxy, get request to port 80 and then forards 
   the requests to port 5000 for flask application running inside docker container )--> Docker container --> Flask 

5. What is keypair, security group?
A: Key pair: it has 2 keys : public and private key, AWS stores the public key and we have the private key. when we try to login aws validates the public key with     
   our private key and then allows us to login to server
   Security group: It acts a virtual firewall to our ec2. it controls the traffic and allows it based on the port we give access to.

6. Diff between sg and nacl?
A: Security group --> for instance level, only allow rule, stateful, easy to manage
   NACL --> subnet level, allow and deny rules, stateless, little difficult to control
    Stateful means If an inbound request is allowed, the response traffic is automatically allowed without creating an outbound rule
    
